Mr Lewis gives the letter Z as a prime example, claiming that by today's standards it should only be worth six points instead of the traditional 10.

He also suggests that X - worth eight points in the current game - should only be worth five points.

But while many of the letters would decrease in value under the system devised by Mr Lewis, some letters would go up in value.

Mr Lewis recommends that the letter U increase from one point to two points and G go from two to three. Q, however, is still apparently a tricky word to play and should still count as 10 points, Mr Lewis adds.

Researcher Joshua Lewis has made a new scoring system so the value of letters better represent how often they are used in the modern day English language.

